 of Spices and Condiments|publisher=Sterling Publishers|isbn=978-1-84557-585-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AaTpWEIlgNwC}}\n-->\n* {{Citation|editor-last=Hanelt|editor-first=P.|year=2001|title=Mansfeld's Encyclopedia of Agricultural and Horticultural Crops|edition=1st|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-540-41017-1<!--3540410171-->|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=10IMFSavIMsC}}\n* {{Citation|last=McGee|first=H.|author-link=Harold McGee|year=2004|title=On Food and Cooking: The Science and Lore of the Kitchen|publisher=Scribner|isbn=978-0-684-80001-1<!--0684800012-->|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iX05JaZXRz0C}}\n* {{Citation|editor-last=Negbi|editor-first=M.|year=1999|title=Saffron: ''Crocus sativus'' L.|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-90-5702-394-1<!--9057023946-->|url=https://books.google.com/?id=l-QJaUp31T4C}}\n* {{Citation|last=Rau|first=S. R.|year=1969|title=The Cooking of India|series=Foods of the World|publisher=[[Time-Life]] Books|isbn=978-0-8094-0069-0<!--0809400693-->}}\n* {{Citation|last=Russo|first=E.|last2=Dreher|first2=M. C.|last3=Mathre|first3=M. L.|year=2003|title=Women and Cannabis: Medicine, Science, and Sociology|edition=1st|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-7890-2101-4<!--0789021013-->}}\n* {{Citation|last=Willard|first=P.|year=2002|title=Secrets of Saffron: The Vagabond Life of the World's Most Seductive Spice|publisher=Beacon Press|isbn=978-0-8070-5009-5<!--0807050083-->|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WsUaFT7l3QsC}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--BLOGS AND COMMERCIAL SITES WILL BE REMOVED. SEE [[WP:EL]].-->\n{{Americana Poster}}\n* {{Citation|title=Saffron|work=Darling Biomedical Library|publisher=[[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]|url=http://unitproj.library.ucla.edu/biomed/spice/index.cfm?displayID=22}}\n* {{Citation|title=''Crocus sativus''|work=Germplasm Resources Information Network|publisher=[[United States Department of Agriculture|USDA]]|url=http://sun.ars-grin.gov:8080/npgspub/xsql/duke/plantdisp.xsql?taxon=318|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041110054340/http://sun.ars-grin.gov:8080/npgspub/xsql/duke/plantdisp.xsql?taxon=318|archive-date=10 November 2004|df=dmy-all}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Related articles\n| list = \n{{Dyeing}}\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[Pharmacodynamics]]\n| titlestyle = background:#ccccff\n| list1 = \n{{Ionotropic glutamate receptor modulators}}<!--\n{{Monoamine reuptake inhibitors}}-->\n{{Sigma receptor modulators}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Saffron| ]]\n[[Category:Crocus|Saffron]]\n[[Category:Food colorings]]\n[[Category:Incense material]]\n[[Category:Arab cuisine]]\n[[Category:Indian spices]]\n[[Category:Iranian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Iraqi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Spices]]\n", "name_user": "151.248.176.169", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Removed inappropriate comma.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saffron"}
{"title_page": "Random! Cartoons", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Random! Cartoons\n| image                    = Random03.jpg\n| genre                    = [[Comedy]]<br />[[Variety show|Variety]]\n| creator                  = '''Main:'''<br />Various<br />'''Supervising:'''<br />[[Fred Seibert]]\n| starring                 = Various\n| composer                 = Various\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| network                  = [[Nicktoons (American TV channel)|Nicktoons Network]]\n| executive_producer       = Fred Seibert<br />[[Larry Huber]]\n| producer                 = Kevin Kolde<br />Therese Trujillo <small>(line producer)</small>\n| company                  = [[Frederator Studios|Frederator Incorporated]]<br />[[Nickelodeon Animation Studio]]\n| num_episodes             = 13 (39 segments)\n| runtime                  = 30 minutes <small>(7 minutes per segment)</small>\n| first_aired              = {{start date|2008|12|06}}\n| last_aired               = {{end date|2009|08|14}}\n| preceded_by              = ''[[Oh Yeah! Cartoons]]''\n| followed_by              = ''[[Nickelodeon Animated Shorts Program]]''\n| related                  = ''[[Fanboy & Chum Chum]]''<br />''[[Adventure Time]]''<br />''[[Bravest Warriors]]''\n| website                  = http://frederator.com/series/random/\n}}\n'''''[https://frederator.com/series/random/ Random]! Cartoons''''' is a 2008-2009 [[United States|American]] [[animation]] showcase television series.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=489}}</ref> Much like ''[[Oh Yeah! Cartoons]]'', it was created by [[Fred Seibert]] and produced by [[Frederator Studios|Frederator Incorporated]]<ref>[http://frederator.com/series/random/ Frederator TV Series]</ref> and [[Nickelodeon Animation Studio]] for [[Nicktoons (American TV channel)|Nicktoons]], and was the fourth of their cartoon \"laboratories\".<ref>[http://frederator.com/series/ Frederator TV Series @ frederator.com]</ref> It premiered on December 6, 2008 and ended on August 14, 2009.\n\n==Production==\nCreator [[Fred Seibert]]<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/84568447@N00/2421744030/ Frederator Studios Flickr | Fred Seibert's Blog | Frederator Postcards Series 6.12<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> ordered thirteen full-length episodes (39 seven-minute shorts) for the series, which was originally announced in 2005 as season four of ''[[Oh Yeah! Cartoons]]''. Production on the series started in 2005 and ended in 2006\u201307. Originally slated for a 2006\u201307 release on [[Nickelodeon]], it was later halted for release in 2008 on the newly formed [[Nicktoons (United States)|Nicktoons Network]] channel.\n\nUnlike ''Oh Yeah! Cartoons'', there is no host. On January 10, 2006, [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] hosted an advance screening of six shorts as well as a Q&A session with the filmmakers at the Nicktoons Studios in [[Burbank, California]]. Two of the shorts were selected to become television series and one of the shorts was selected to become a web series. Those shorts were ''Adventure Time'', ''The Bravest Warriors'' and ''Fanboy''. ''[[Adventure Time]]'' began airing as a full-length series on April 5, 2010 on [[Cartoon Network]].<ref>[http://adventuretime.frederator.com/post/449695884/cartoon-network-premieres-adventure-time-with-finn-jake Cartoon Network Premieres \u201cAdventure Time with Finn &amp; Jake\u201d on April 5, 2010 Frederator.com March 1, 2010]</ref> ''The Bravest Warriors'', under the new name ''[[Bravest Warriors]]'', began airing on November 8, 2012 on [[Cartoon Hangover]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mpDOscUDQ_0&list=PL2DcNkn8HAwSPwGn9h2GGM4Z0t6B0ySVD Cartoon Hangover November 8, 2012]</ref> ''Fanboy'', under the new name ''[[Fanboy & Chum Chum]]'', began airing as a full-length series on November 7, 2009 on Nickelodeon.\n\nSince the series' cancellation, reruns continued to air until August 31, 2014.\n\n==List of shorts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=10 style=\"background-color: #00BFFF\" | Prod. no.\n! width=321 style=\"background-color: #00BFFF\" | Segment\n! width=110 style=\"background-color: #00BFFF\" | Creator\n! width=75 style=\"background-color: #00BFFF\" | Original airdate\n! width=75 style=\"background-color: #00BFFF\" | Synopsis\n! width=50 style=\"background-color: #00BFFF\" | Cast\n! width=50 style=\"background-color: #00BFFF\" | Series/Short\n|- style=\"background-color: #e9e9e9;\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1 || \"''Solomon Fix''\" || [[Doug TenNapel]] || December 6, 2008 || A teddy bear named Solomon Fix is assigned to protect a child named Ned, only that the child finds him lame. || [[Rob Paulsen]] as Solomon Fix<br />[[John DiMaggio]] as Mumpy<br />[[Maurice LaMarche]] as Klemp<br />Elijah Runcorn as Ned<br />[[Doug TenNapel]] as Chipmonk#1 & 2 || Short\n|- style=\"background-color: #e9e9e9;\n| \"''MooBeard the Cow Pirate''\" || Kyle Carrozza || December 6, 2008 || A cow pirate named MooBeard along with his companion Sailor Bird searches the treasure of the lost island of Hookamookapookalap. || [[Billy West (voice actor)|Billy West]] as MooBeard / Value Guy<br />[[Erica Luttrell]] as Sailor Bird / Road Show Announcer<br />[[Dave \"Gruber\" Allen]] as Darkblade of Fire<br />Kyle Carrozza as Ungus the Unpleasant / Cow Eating Gentleman|| Short\n|- style=\"background-color: #e9e9e9;\"\n| \"''Two Witch Sisters''\" || [[Niki Yang]] || December 6, 2008 || Twin witch sisters are causing magic-induced havoc at a park.|| [[S. Scott Bullock]] as Dorothy / Hummingbird<br />[[Dee Bradley Baker]] as Carrot / Seymour<br />[[Candi Milo]] as Bee<br />Niki Yang as Baby Rabbit|| Short\n|- style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2 || \"''The Finster Finster Show!'': Store Wars''\" || [[Jeff DeGrandis]] || December 7, 2008 || Two Finsters battle anthropomorphic frozen chickens in the supermarket. || Billy West as Finster 1<br />[[Charlie Adler]] as Finster 2<br />[[Tress MacNeille]] as Finsters' Mom || Short\n|- style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"\n| \"''[[Adventure Time (pilot)|Adventure Time]]''\" || [[Pendleton Ward]] || December 7, 2008 || In this precursor to the critically acclaimed full-length series, [[Finn the Human|Finn]] (known as \"Penn\" in the short) and [[Jake the Dog|Jake]] battle the [[Ice King]] to save [[Princess Bubblegum]]. || [[Zack Shada]] as Penn<br />John DiMaggio as Jake / Ice Clops<br />[[Paige Moss]] as Princess Bubblegum<br />[[John Kassir]] as Ice King / Fire Element<br />[[Dee Bradley Baker]] as Lady Rainicorn / Snow Golem<br />[[Pendleton Ward]] as Abraham Lincoln / Old Man|| TV Series\n|- style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"\n| \"''Mind the Kitty''\" || Anne Walker || December 7, 2008 || Three teens have to babysit a psychotic kitten girl. || Dee Bradley Baker as the Duck/Tabby<br />[[Jeff Bennett]] as Punky<br />[[Rodger Bumpass]] as Lemurman<br />[[Lynne Maclean]] as Tabby's Mom || Short\n|- style=\"background-color: #e9e9e9;\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 3 || \"''Ivan the Unbearable''\" || Andrew Dickman || December 13, 2008 || A clumsy Viking gets hiccups that causes destruction. || [[Jeff Doucette]] as Ivan the Unbearable/Olaf<br />Maurice LaMarche as Bjorn/Working Troll #1<br />Tress MacNeille as Ma<br />Andrew Dickman as Filthy Viking/Working Troll #2 || Short\n|- style=\"background-color: #e9e9e9;\"\n| \"''Boneheads''\" || Hadley Hudson || December 13, 2008 || Roccos and Bone search for babanas. || [[John Kassir]] as Bone/Soldier Flies<br />[[Dee Bradley Baker]] as Roccos/Audrey/Antarctic Bull Snail/Rex<br/>Hadley Hudson as Striker (uncredited) || Short\n|- style=\"background-color: #e9e9e9;\"\n| \"''Tiffany''\" || Adam Henry || December 13, 2008 || A doll must help her friend overcome a fear of horses. || Jessie Flower as Peggy<br />[[Colleen Vi