{"title_page": "Adrian Clayborn", "text_new": "{{Current sports transaction|trans=free agent signing|sport=American football}}\n\n{{short description|American football defensive end}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Adrian Clayborn\n|image=Adrian Clayborn 2015.jpg\n|image_size=\n|alt=\n|caption=Clayborn with the Atlanta Falcons in 2015\n|current_team =Free agent\n|number= \n|position=[[Defensive end]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1988|7|6|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[St. Louis, Missouri]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 3\n|weight_lbs = 280\n|high_school = [[Webster Groves High School|Webster Groves]]<br/>([[Webster Groves, Missouri]])\n|college=[[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa]]\n|draftyear=2011\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=20\n|pastteams=\n* [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] ({{NFL Year|2011}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2014}})\n* [[Atlanta Falcons]] ({{NFL Year|2015}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2017}})\n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|2018}})\n* Atlanta Falcons ({{NFL Year|2019}})\n<!--* [[Cleveland Browns]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)-->\n|status=\n|highlights=\n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]])\n* Consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2010 College Football All-America Team|2010]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] ([[2009 All-Big Ten Conference football team|2009]], [[2010 All-Big Ten Conference football team|2010]])\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue1=196\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n|statvalue2=36.5\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue3=10\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue4=4\n|statlabel5=[[Touchdown|Defensive touchdowns]] \n|statvalue5=0\n|nfl=CLA770145\n}}\n\n'''Adrian Jarrell Clayborn''' (born July 6, 1988) is an [[American football]] [[defensive end]] who is currently a free agent. He played [[college football]] for the [[University of Iowa]], and earned consensus [[All-American]] honors. He was drafted by the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] in the first round of the [[2011 NFL Draft]].\n\n==Personal life==\nClayborn was born in [[St. Louis, Missouri]]. At birth, he suffered from a condition known as [[Erb's Palsy]], something that is caused during birth by an injury to the nerves surrounding a child's shoulder. Because his head and neck were pulled to the side as his shoulders passed through the birth canal, he suffered nerve damage resulting in the loss of some movement and weakness in his right arm.<ref>{{cite news |title=Late bloomer Clayborn becoming dominant leader |url=http://thegazette.com/2009/11/06/late-bloomer-clayton-becoming-dominant-leader/ |publisher=The Gazette|date=November 10, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2010}}</ref> Clayborn underwent physical therapy throughout his young life and eventually overcame the limitations caused by the disorder.\n\nWhen Adrian was 10, his older brother Anthony was shot and killed in northern St. Louis. He was survived by his seven children: Asia, Aaliyah, Andrea, Anthony Junior, Demonte, Leaunte, and Keith.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spotlight on Adrian Clayborn: Close to it All |url=http://www.kcrg.com/sports/hawkeyes/Clayborn-Close-to-it-All-100147949.html |publisher=The Gazette |date=August 10, 2010 |accessdate=August 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314154427/http://www.kcrg.com/sports/hawkeyes/Clayborn-Close-to-it-All-100147949.html |archivedate=March 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAdrian and his wife Shannon volunteer at the Hesed House homeless shelter in Aurora, IL.\n\n==High school career==\nClayborn attended high school at [[Webster Groves High School]], where he was a four-year [[Letterman (sports)|letterman]] in [[high school football|football]] and basketball.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ksdk.com/article/sports/nfl/webster-groves-high-grad-adrian-clayborn-has-6-sacks-falcons-romp-past-cowboys-27-7/63-491389071 |title=Webster Groves High grad Adrian Clayborn has 6 sacks, Falcons romp past Cowboys 27-7 |website=KSDK |language=en-US |access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honors===\n*2005 Missouri Player of the Year\n*2005 Missouri All-State\n*2004 Missouri All-State<ref>[http://www.hawkeyesports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/clayborn_adrian00.html Player Bio: Adrian Clayborn - Iowa Official Athletic Site<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501103648/http://www.hawkeyesports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/clayborn_adrian00.html |date=May 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nClayborn attended the [[University of Iowa]], and played for the [[Iowa Hawkeyes football]] team from 2006 to 2010. He took a [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] year in 2006, his first season at Iowa. In 2007, Clayborn became a second-string defensive lineman and saw action in several games on special teams. In 2008, Clayborn saw substantial playing time, recording 8 tackles for loss and 50 total tackles. In 2009, Clayborn had a breakout year with 20 tackles for loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/adrian-clayborn-1/gamelog/2009 |title=Adrian Clayborn 2009 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 13, 2017}}</ref> In a dominant effort against [[Georgia Tech]], Clayborn was named Orange Bowl MVP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcrg.com/sports/80854112.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110092356/http://www.kcrg.com/sports/80854112.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 10, 2010|title=Iowa's Clayborn the Dominant Orange Bowl MVP - KCRG-TV9 - Cedar Rapids, Iowa News, Sports, and Weather - Sports|date=January 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHeading into the 2010 season, Clayborn was listed on the preseason watch list for several awards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maxwell Football Club Announces Maxwell And Bednarik Watch Lists |url=http://www.maxwellfootballclub.org/maxwell-football-club-announces-maxwell-and-bednarik-watch-lists |publisher=[[Maxwell Football Club]] |date=August 9, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100814162810/http://www.maxwellfootballclub.org/maxwell-football-club-announces-maxwell-and-bednarik-watch-lists |archivedate=August 14, 2010 }}</ref> [[ESPN]], [[Playboy Magazine]], [[Sporting News]], College Football Insiders, Lindy's, and [[Phil Steele]] all selected Clayborn for their pre-season first team All-American lists.\n\nOn October 2, 2010, Clayborn had his first break-out game of 2010. He had three tackles for loss against Penn State despite being triple-teamed for parts of the game. His play earned him Big Ten Defensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iowa, Michigan, Michigan State and Wisconsin Collect Weekly Football Laurels |url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/100410aaa.html |publisher=[[Big Ten Conference]] |access-date=November 11, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101010205745/http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/100410aaa.html |archive-date=October 10, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On November 10, 2010, Clayborn was named one of four finalists for the [[Rotary Lombardi Award]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Clayborn One of Four Finalists for Rotary Lombardi Award |url=http://www.hawkeyesports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/111010aae.html |publisher=Hawkeye Sports}}</ref>\n\nWhile preparing for the 2010 [[Insight Bowl]], Iowa head coach [[Kirk Ferentz]] announced that Clayborn was one of three Hawkeyes invited to attend the [[Senior Bowl]], college football's pre-draft event featuring seniors with [[NFL]] prospects.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iowa Football: Stanzi, Clayborn, Ballard Invited to Senior Bowl |url=http://www.iowahawkeyes.net/blog/post.cfm?p=iowa-football--stanzi--clayborn--ballard-invited-to-senior-bowl |publisher=Hawkeye Nerd |work=iowahawkeyes.net |date=December 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honors===\n\n====2010====\n*Consensus First-team All-American by NCAA,<ref>{{cite news|title=NCAA names Adrian Clayborn consensus all-American |url=http://hawkcentral.com/2010/12/20/ncaa-names-adrian-clayborn-consensus-all-american/ |work=hawkcentral.com |publisher=Hawk Central |date=December 20, 2010 |accessdate=December 20, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223121740/http://hawkcentral.com/2010/12/20/ncaa-names-adrian-clayborn-consensus-all-american/ |archivedate=December 23, 2010 }}</ref> AFCA<ref>{{cite news |title=Iowa's Clayborn named third-team All-America |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/wire/chi-ap-fbc-iowa-clayborn,0,2531021.story |work=chicagotribune.com |publisher=Chicago Tribune |date=December 15, 2010 |accessdate=December 20, 2010}}</ref> and Walter Camp.<ref>{{cite news|title=121st Walter Camp All-America teams announced |url=http://college-football.blogs.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/24156338/26347880 |work=cbssports.com |publisher=CBS Sports |date=December 9, 2010 |accessdate=December 20, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101216081952/http://college-football.blogs.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/24156338/26347880 |archivedate=December 16, 2010 }}</ref>\n*First Team All-Big Ten (Coaches, Media)<ref>{{cite news |title=3 Hawks defenders earn first-team all-Big Ten honors |url=http://qctimes.com/sports/college/big-10/iowa/article_a89816ec-fc3d-11df-9f39-001cc4c002e0.html |work=qctimes.com |publisher=Quad City Times |date=November 29, 2010 |accessdate=December 6, 2010}}</ref>\n*American Football Coaches Association First Team All-American<ref>{{cite news |title=Clayborn Named First Team All-American |url=http://www.hawkeyesports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/112910aac.html |work=hawkeyesports.com |publisher=Hawkeye Sports |date=November 29, 2010 |accessdate=December 6, 2010}}</ref>\n*Ted Hendricks Award Finalist<ref>{{cite news|title=Iowa's Clayborn Named Hendricks Finalists |url=http://www.kcrg.com/sports/local/Iowas-Clayborn-Named-Hendricks-Finalists--111119679.html |publisher=[[KCRG-TV|KCRG]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314154443/http://www.kcrg.com/sports/local/Iowas-Clayborn-Named-Hendricks-Finalists--111119679.html |archivedate=March 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n*Rotary Lombardi Award Finalist\n*Rotary Lombardi Award Pre-season Watch List\n*Bednarik Award Semi-finalist<ref>{{cite news |title=2010 Maxwell and Bednarik Award Semifinalists |url=http://www.maxwellfootballclub.org/news/2010-maxwell-and-bednarik-award-semifinalists |publisher=[[Maxwell Football Club]] |access-date=November 11, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111005209/http://www.maxwellfootballclub.org/news/2010-maxwell-and-bednarik-award-semifinalists |archive-date=November 11, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*Bednarik Award Pre-season Watch List\n*Walter Camp Player of the Year Watch List\n*[[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]] Watch List <ref>{{cite news |title=2010 Bronko Nagurski Trophy Watch List Announced |url=http://www.sportswriters.net/fwaa/news/2010/nagurski100621.html |publisher=[[Football Writers Association of America]] |date=June 21, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2010}}</ref>\n*Playboy Magazine Pre-season All-America Team selection<ref>{{cite news |title=Four Big Ten Players Land on 2010 Playboy All-America Team |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/403924-four-big-ten-players-land-on-2010-playboy-all-america-team |publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]}}</ref>\n*College Football Performance Award Honorable Mention<ref>{{cite news |title=Clayborn and Prater Earn Performance Awards |url=http://www.hawkeyesports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/100310aaj.html |publisher=Hawkeye Sports}}</ref>\n*Big Ten Defensive Player of the Week \u2013 October 4, 2010\n\n====2009====\n*Big Ten Player of the Week \u2013 October 25, 2009\n*Big Ten Defensive Player of The Week<ref>{{cite news |title=Big Ten Honor Roll: Tracking the Big Ten Conference's Players of the Week |url=http://www.bigtennetwork.com/blogs/index.asp?post_id=3258|work=bigtennetwork.com |publisher=[[Big Ten Network]] |date=October 25, 2009 |accessdate=August 16, 2010}}</ref>\n*[[2010 Orange Bowl]] MVP<!-- The 2010 Orange Bowl follows the 2009 season -->\n\n==Professional career==\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 2\u215d\n|       weight = 281\n|         dash = 4.78\n|    ten split = 1.61\n| twenty split = 2.69\n|      shuttle = 4.13\n|   cone drill = 7.08\n|     vertical = 35\u00bd\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 6\n|        bench = 17\n|    wonderlic = x\n|     arm span = 32\u00bd\n|    hand span = 9\u00be\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine and Iowa Pro Day<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=64808&draftyear=2011&genpos=DE|title=Adrian Clayborn - Iowa, DE : 2011 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile|website=www.nfldraftscout.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/adrian-clayborn?id=2495140|title=NFL Events: Combine Player Profiles - Adrian Clayborn|website=www.nfl.com}}</ref><ref>http://insider.espn.com/nfl/draft/player/_/id/26085</ref>}}\n\n===Tampa Bay Buccaneers===\nClayborn was drafted in the first round (20th overall) of the [[2011 NFL Draft]] by the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011/draft.htm |title=2011 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref> Clayborn recorded his first sack in week 3 of the 2011 season against the [[Atlanta Falcons]]. His sack on [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] also caused a fumble recovered by teammate [[Michael Bennett (defensive lineman, born 1985)|Michael Bennett]]. In 2012, Clayborn was placed on injured reserve after injuring his knee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000065853/article/bucs-adrian-clayborn-out-for-season-with-knee-injury?module=HP11_headline_stack |title=Bucs' Adrian Clayborn out for season with knee injury |publisher=NFL.com |date= |accessdate=September 24, 2012}}</ref> Before the 2014 season, it was announced by new GM [[Jason Licht]] that the Buccaneers would not be picking up the 5th year option on his rookie contract. He was also moved to the left side since the team signed [[Michael Johnson (defensive end)|Michael Johnson]] for the right side. Though he started out strong in the year, he suffered yet another season-ending injury placing him on IR and his future in Tampa in doubt since he would be an unrestricted free agent in 2015.\n\n===Atlanta Falcons===\n[[File:Adrian Clayborn.JPG|175px|thumb|right|Clayborn in 2016.]]\nOn March 12, 2015, Clayborn signed with the [[Atlanta Falcons]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Falcons free agency: Adrian Clayborn, Phillip Adams sign with Atlanta Thursday|url=http://www.thefalcoholic.com/2015/3/12/8203029/falcons-free-agency-adrian-clayborn-phillip-adams-sign-with-atlanta|publisher=Bleacher Report|author=Choate, Dave|date=March 12, 2015|accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/article-1/Falcons-Add-More-Defensive-Help-in-Free-Agency/05b57e02-f8b5-4ea1-af7c-aeb2ffd61fb1|title=Falcons Add More Defensive Help in Free Agency|work=AtlantaFalcons.com|first=Jay|last=Adams|date=March 12, 2015|accessdate=March 12, 2015|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6X5GaUAFD?url=http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/article-1/Falcons-Add-More-Defensive-Help-in-Free-Agency/05b57e02-f8b5-4ea1-af7c-aeb2ffd61fb1|archive-date=March 17, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On March 9, 2016, he re-signed with the Falcons on a two-year deal worth $9 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Falcons Agree To Terms With Clayborn, Shelby|url=http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/blog/article-1/Falcons-Agree-to-Terms-With-Clayborn-Shelby/b4a6c267-9e19-4814-b9bc-5d75790885b4|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002165844/http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/blog/article-1/Falcons-Agree-to-Terms-With-Clayborn-Shelby/b4a6c267-9e19-4814-b9bc-5d75790885b4|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 2, 2017|website=AtlantaFalcons.com|date=March 10, 2016|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> He played in 13 games with seven starts recording 22 tackles and 4.5 sacks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/C/ClayAd00/gamelog/2016/ |title=Adrian Clayborn 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 15, 2017}}</ref> In the divisional round of the playoffs, Clayborn suffered a torn bicep and was placed on injured reserve on January 17, 2017, causing him to miss the rest of the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Falcons place Adrian Clayborn on IR, promote DL Joe Vellano|url=http://www.thefalcoholic.com/2017/1/17/14303472/falcons-place-adrian-clayborn-on-ir-promote-dl-joe-vellano-oh-shit-no|author=Chambers, Matthew|website=TheFalcoholic.com|date=January 17, 2017}}</ref> Without Clayborn, the Falcons reached [[Super Bowl LI]] where they lost 34-28 in overtime to the [[New England Patriots]].\n\nOn November 12, 2017, in Week 10 against the [[2017 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], Clayborn recorded a franchise-record six sacks, one away from tying [[Derrick Thomas]]' record of seven, as the Falcons won the game 27\u20137.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adrian Clayborn's six sacks power Falcons past Cowboys|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000876146/article/adrian-clayborns-sacks-power-falcons-past-cowboys|publisher=NFL|accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sessler|first1=Marc|title=Adrian Clayborn's six sacks earned $750K pay day|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000876534/article/adrian-clayborns-six-sacks-earned-750k-pay-day|publisher=NFL|accessdate=November 13, 2017}}</ref> He was named the NFC Defensive Player of the Week days later.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Brady, Cam Newton among Players of the Week|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000877642/article/tom-brady-cam-newton-among-players-of-the-week|author=Maya, Adam|website=NFL.com|date=November 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Knoblauch|first1=Austin|title=Adrian Clayborn considered retiring before season|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000878349/article/adrian-clayborn-considered-retiring-before-season|publisher=NFL|accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref> Heading into the 2018 NFL season, the six sacks in one game account for one-fifth of Clayborn's career sack total of 30.\n\n===New England Patriots===\nOn March 17, 2018, Clayborn signed a two-year $10 million contract with the [[New England Patriots]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.patriots.com/news/patriots-sign-three-free-agents-327361|title=Patriots Sign Three Free Agents|website=Patriots.com|date=March 17, 2018|access-date=March 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318072719/http://www.patriots.com/news/2018/03/17/patriots-sign-three-free-agents|archive-date=March 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In Clayborn's first season in New England, Clayborn recorded 11 tackles and 2.5 sacks. With Clayborn, the Patriots went on to win [[Super Bowl LIII]] 13\u20133 against the [[Los Angeles Rams]] to give Clayborn his first championship.<ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/oliverthomas/2019/02/12/patriots-adrian-clayborn-a-veteran-pass-rusher-worth-keeping-around/#59f5e3863c88</ref>\n\nOn March 15, 2019, Clayborn was released by the Patriots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nesn.com/2019/03/patriots-release-adrian-clayborn-clear-4m-in-salary-cap-space/|title=Patriots Release Adrian Clayborn, Clear $4M In Salary Cap Space|last=Cox|first=Zach|date=March 15, 2019|website=NESN|access-date=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Atlanta Falcons (second stint) ===\nOn April 9, 2019, Clayborn signed a one-year $4 million contract with the Atlanta Falcons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/falcons-agree-to-terms-with-adrian-clayborn-on-a-one-year-contract|title=Falcons agree to terms with Adrian Clayborn on a one-year contract|website=AtlantaFalcons.com|date=April 9, 2019}}</ref> In Week 2 against the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], Clayborn recorded his first sack of the season in the 24\u201320 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128124 |title=Jones scores late TD, leads Falcons past Eagles 24-20 |date=15 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> In Week 10 against the [[2019 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], Clayborn had one sack in the 26\u20139 win. In Week 11 against the [[2019 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], Clayborn had two sacks in the 29\u20133 win. Clayborn played in 15 games with one start, recording 18 tackles, 4.0 sacks and 2 forced fumbles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/C/ClayAd00.htm|title=Adrian Clayborn Stats|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Cleveland Browns ===\nOn March 31, 2020, it was reported that Clayborn had signed a two-year $6  million contract with the [[Cleveland Browns]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2020/03/31/browns-sign-adrian-clayborn/|title=Browns sign Adrian Clayborn|website=Pro Football Talk|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The Browns have yet to formally announce the deal.\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! {{tooltip|GP|Games played}} !! {{tooltip|GS|Games started}} !! {{tooltip|COMB|Combined tackles}} !! {{tooltip|TOTAL|Total tackles}} !! {{tooltip|AST|Assisted tackles}} !! {{tooltip|SACK|Sacks}} !! {{tooltip|FF|Forced fumbles}} !! {{tooltip|FR|Fumble recoveries}} !! {{tooltip|FR YDS|Fumble return yards}} !! {{tooltip|INT|Interceptions}} !! {{tooltip|IR YDS|Interception return yards}} !! {{tooltip|AVG IR|Average interception return}} !! {{tooltip|LNG|Longest interception return}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Interceptions/Fumbles returned for touchdown}} !! {{tooltip|PD|Passes defensed}}\n|-\n! [[20